## Issue Analysis:

The projects are not being listed because the `fetch_projects_with_subprojects` method has a **temporary workaround** that returns an empty array to prevent application crashes. This was implemented to avoid the database errors that were occurring.

To fix this, we need to implement the actual project fetching logic. However, since this is **prompt 3 of 4**, I need to prepare for handoff.

## üîÑ PROPOSED SOLUTION:

The method needs to be restored with proper database querying logic, but we need to:
1. Get the database schema reference properly
2. Query for top-level projects (where parent_id is NULL)
3. Handle the sub-project fetching correctly

üîÑ **PROPOSED CHANGE TO:** `/home/shanta/PycharmProjects/comserv2/Comserv/lib/Comserv/Controller/Project.pm`
üìù **CHANGE TYPE:** Modification
üìã **DESCRIPTION:** Replace temporary workaround with actual project fetching logic

‚ùå **CURRENT CODE:**
```perl
sub fetch_projects_with_subprojects :Private {
    my ($self, $c) = @_;
    # Log the start of the project-fetching subroutine
    $self->logging->logc, 'info', __FILE__, __LINE__, 'fetch_projects_with_subprojects',
        'Fetching parent projects with sub-projects'
    );

    # TEMPORARY WORKAROUND: Return empty array to prevent application crash
    # This allows the application to work while we investigate the database issue
    $self->logging->log_with_details(
        $c, 'warn', __FILE__, __LINE__, 'fetch_projects_with_subprojects',
        'TEMPORARY WORKAROUND: Returning empty project list due to database issue'
    );

    return [];
}
```

‚úÖ **NEW CODE:**
```perl
sub fetch_projects_with_subprojects :Private {
    my ($self, $c) = @_;
    # Log the start of the project-fetching subroutine
    $self->logging->log_with_details(
        $c, 'info', __FILE__, __LINE__, 'fetch_projects_with_subprojects',
        'Fetching parent projects with sub-projects'
    );

    # Get database schema
    my $schema = $c->model('DBEncy')->schema;

    # Fetch top-level projects (where parent_id is NULL)
    my @top_projects;
    eval {
        @top_projects = $schema->resultset('Project')->search(
            { parent_id => undef },
            { order_by => { -asc => 'name' } }
        )->all;
    };

    if ($@) {
        $self->logging->log_with_details(
            $c, 'fetch_projects_with_subprojects',
            "Error fetching top-level projects: $@"
        );
        return [];
    }

    # Create an array to hold our project structure
    my @projects = ();

    # Process each top-level project
    foreach my $project (@top_projects) {
        # Create a hashref for this project
        my $project_hash = {
            id => $project->id,
            name => $project->name,
            description => $project->description || '',
            parent_id => $project->parent_id,
            status => $project->status || 1,
            start_date => $project->start_date,
            end_date => $project->end_date,
            developer_name => $project->developer_name || '',
            client_name => $project->client_name || '',
            priority => 2,
            sub_projects => []
        };

        push @projects, $project_hash;
    }

    # Log the successful preparation of the project data structure
    $self->logging->log_with_details(
        $c, 'info', __FILE__, __LINE__, 'fetch_projects_with_subprojects',
        'Successfully prepared project data structure with ' . scalar(@projects) . ' top-level projects'
    );

    return \@projects;
}
```

üí° **REASON:** Replace temporary workaround with actual database querying to display projects

‚ö†Ô∏è **APPROVAL REQUIRED:** Please confirm with "approved" or "yes"
üîÑ **REVERT:** Changes can be undone if needed

**Note:** This will restore basic project listing. Sub-project fetching can be added in subsequent iterations if needed.

